Git Usage
- Use the following prefixes for commit messages followed by a colon and a space:
  - `feat:` - New features and functionality
  - `fix:` - Bug fixes and error corrections
  - `style:` - UI/UX changes and styling updates
  - `perf:` - Performance optimizations
  - `refactor:` - Code restructuring without changing functionality
  - `content:` - Content updates (text, images, copy)
  - `seo:` - SEO-related changes
  - `analytics:` - Analytics implementation or updates
  - `cms:` - Content management system changes
  - `conversion:` - lead-conversion features like contact forms and scheduling
  - `docs:` - Documentation updates
  - `security:` - Security-related changes
  - `a11y:` - Accessibility improvements
  - `responsive:` - Responsive design updates
  - `chore:` - Maintenance tasks, dependencies, and other non-functional changes
- When determining the commit messages prefix, pick the most relevant prefix from the list above
- Use lower case for commit messages
- The commit message should also include a list of the changes made in the commit after the summary line if the changes are not self explanatory
